[Thank you Dr. King for submitting this report. _Angiostrongylus
(Parastrongylus) cantonensis_ , also known as the rat lungworm, is a
nematode. In the outbreak reported on ProMED-mail in 2000, the implicated
food may have been a Caesar salad consumed by the students. Other outbreaks
and cases have been associated with the consumption of raw or
insufficiently cooked snails, slugs, or land planarians, which are
intermediate or transport hosts harboring infective larvae. Prawns, fish,
and land crabs that have ingested snails or slugs may also transport the
infective larvae. Lettuce and other leafy vegetables contaminated by small
molluscs may serve as a source of infection. The molluscs are infected by
first-stage larvae excreted by an infected rodent. From the above report it
is possible that the source of infection was either the salads or the
seafood (unspecified).
As Dr. King rightly states, this case further highlights the continued risk
of food-borne transmission of _Angiostrongylus_ in Jamaica. - Mod.MPP
...............................jw/mpp/pg/ep/ds
